ory:Government of Andorra]]\n[[Category:HEC Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Lyc\u00e9e Pasteur alumni]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in France]]\n[[Category:People from Rouen]]\n[[Category:People of the Central African Republic Civil War (2012\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:People of the Ukrainian crisis]]\n[[Category:Princes of Andorra]]\n[[Category:Sciences Po alumni]]\n[[Category:Socialist Party (France) politicians]]\n<!-- Honours -->\n[[Category:Collars of the Order of Isabella the Catholic]]\n[[Category:Grand Croix of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Grand Cross of the National Order of Merit (France)]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of Saint-Charles]]\n[[Category:Honorary Knights Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross with Collar of the Order of Merit of the Italian Republic]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Liberty (Ukraine)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Liberator General San Martin]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Phoenix (Greece)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French official and statesman}}\n{{redirect|Hollande||Holland (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name           = Fran\u00e7ois Hollande\n|image          = Francois Hollande 2015.jpeg\n|caption        = Hollande in 2015\n|office         = [[President of France]]\n|primeminister  = [[Jean-Marc Ayrault]]<br />[[Manuel Valls]]<br />[[Bernard Cazeneuve]]\n|term_start     = 15 May 2012\n|term_end       = 14 May 2017\n|predecessor    = [[Nicolas Sarkozy]]\n|successor      = [[Emmanuel Macron]]\n|office1        = [[List of Presidents of Corr\u00e8ze General Council|President of the General Council of Corr\u00e8ze]]\n|term_start1    = 20 March 2008\n|term_end1      = 15 May 2012\n|predecessor1   = [[Jean-Pierre Dupont]]\n|successor1     = G\u00e9rard Bonnet\n|office2        = [[First Secretary of the French Socialist Party|First Secretary of the Socialist Party]]\n|term_start2    = 27 November 1997\n|term_end2      = 27 November 2008\n|predecessor2   = [[Lionel Jospin]]\n|successor2     = [[Martine Aubry]]\n|office3        = [[List of mayors of Tulle|Mayor of Tulle]]\n|term_start3    = 17 March 2001\n|term_end3      = 17 March 2008\n|predecessor3   = [[Raymond-Max Aubert]]\n|successor3     = [[Bernard Combes]]\n|office4        = Member of the [[National Assembly (France)|National Assembly]]<br />for [[Corr\u00e8ze]]'s [[Corr\u00e8ze's 1st constituency|1st]] constituency\n|term_start4    = 12 June 1997\n|term_end4      = 15 May 2012\n|predecessor4   = Lucien Renaudie\n|successor4     = [[Sophie Dessus]]\n|term_start5    = 12 June 1988\n|term_end5      = 1 April 1993\n|predecessor5   = ''Constituency re-established''\n|successor5     = [[Raymond-Max Aubert]]\n|office6        = [[Member of the European Parliament]]\n|term_start6    = 20 July 1999\n|term_end6      = 17 December 1999\n|constituency6  = [[France (European Parliament constituency)|France]]\n|birth_name     = Fran\u00e7ois G\u00e9rard Georges Nicolas Hollande\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1954|8|12|df=y}}\n|birth_place    = [[Rouen]], [[Seine-Maritime|Seine-Inf\u00e9rieure]], [[France]]\n|death_date     = \n|death_place    = \n|party          = [[Socialist Party (France)|Socialist Party]]\n|partner        = [[S\u00e9gol\u00e8ne Royal]] {{small|(1978\u20132007)}}<br />[[Val\u00e9rie Trierweiler]] {{small|(2007\u20132014)}}<br />[[Julie Gayet]] {{small|(2014\u2013present)}}\n|children       = 4\n|residence      = \n|alma_mater     = [[Panth\u00e9on-Assas University]]<br />[[HEC Paris]]<br />[[Sciences Po]]<br />[[\u00c9cole nationale d'administration]]\n|signature      = Fran\u00e7ois Hollande signature.svg\n}}\n'''Fran\u00e7ois G\u00e9rard Georges Nicolas Hollande''' ({{IPA-fr|f\u0281\u0251\u0303swa \u0292e\u0281a\u0281 \u0292\u0254\u0281\u0292 nik\u0254la \u0254l\u0251\u0303d|lang|Fr-Fran\u00e7ois Hollande.ogg}}; born 12 August 1954) is a French politician who served as [[President of France]] and ''[[Ex officio member|ex officio]]'' [[Co-Princes of Andorra|Co-Prince of Andorra]] from 2012 to 2017. He was previously the [[First Secretary of the French Socialist Party|First Secretary]] of the [[Socialist Party (France)|Socialist Party]] from 1997 to 2008, [[Mayor (France)|Mayor]] of [[Tulle]] from 2001 to 2008, and President of the [[Corr\u00e8ze General Council]] from 2008 to 2012. Hollande also served in the [[National Assembly (France)|National Assembly of France]] twice for the [[Departments of France|department]] of [[Corr\u00e8ze]]'s [[Corr\u00e8ze's 1st constituency|1st]] constituency from 1988 to 1993, and again from 1997 to 2012.\n\nBorn in [[Rouen]] and raised in [[Neuilly-sur-Seine]], Hollande began his political career as a special advisor to newly elected President [[Fran\u00e7ois Mitterrand]], before serving as a staffer for [[Max Gallo]], the government's spokesman. He became a member of the [[National Assembly (France)|National Assembly]] in 1988 and was elected First Secretary of the Socialist Party in 1997. Following the [[2004 French regional elections|2004 regional elections]] won by the Socialists, Hollande was cited as a potential presidential candidate, but resigned as First Secretary and was immediately elected to replace [[Jean-Pierre Dupont]] as President of the [[Departmental council (France)|General Council]] of Corr\u00e8ze in 2008. In 2011, Hollande announced that he would be a candidate in the [[French Socialist Party presidential primary, 2011|primary election]] to select the Socialist Party presidential nominee; he won the nomination and was [[2012 French presidential election|elected]] President of France on 6 May 2012 during the second round of voting with 51.6% of the vote against incumbent [[Nicolas Sarkozy]].\n\nDuring his tenure, Hollande legalised [[Same-sex marriage in France|same-sex marriage]] by passing [[Law 2013-404|Bill no. 344]], reformed [[El Khomri law|labour laws]] and credit training programmes, withdrew French combat troops [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|present in the Afghanistan military intervention]]<ref name=\"guardianAC1\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> and concluded a [[EU Directive 2010/63/EU|EU directive]] through a [[France\u2013Germany relations|Franco-German contract]]. Hollande led the country through the [[Charlie Hebdo shooting|January]] and [[November 2015 Paris attacks|November 2015 Paris]] and [[2016 Nice attack]]s. He was a leading proponent of [[European migrant crisis|EU mandatory migrant quotas]] and [[NATO]]'s 2011 [[2011 military intervention in Libya|military intervention in Libya]]. He also sent troops to [[Mali]] and the [[Central African Republic]] with the approval of the UN Security Council in order to stabilise those countries, two operations largely seen as successful. However his support of the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.sky.com/story/eu-must-be-firm-on-hard-brexit-warns-francois-hollande-10607872|title=EU must be firm on 'hard' Brexit, says Hollande|publisher=Sky News|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-12-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/oct/07/uk-must-pay-price-for-brexit-says-francois-hollande|title=UK must pay price for Brexit, says Fran\u00e7ois Hollande|last=Chrisafis|first=Angelique|date=2016-10-07|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=2016-12-04}}</ref><ref name=\"Horobin\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/french-president-hollande-says-he-wont-run-for-re-election-1480620696|title=French President Fran\u00e7ois Hollande Says He Won't Run for Re-Election|last=Horobin|first=William|date=2016-12-01|newspaper=Wall Street Journal|issn=0099-9660|access-date=2016-12-04}}</ref> drew controversy among his left-wing electoral basis. Under his term, France also became the [[Tourism in France|most toured country in the world]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://us.media.france.fr/en/node/217|title=Tourism is a Top Priority for President Fran\u00e7ois Hollande's Administration {{!}} US Media|website=us.media.france.fr|access-date=2016-12-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.france24.com/en/20160807-tourism-france-still-suffering|title=Tourism in France takes fresh hit from recent terror attacks |date=2016-08-07|publisher=France 24|language=en-US|access-date=2016-12-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sooseszter.com/48-disappointing-growth-suffering-tourism/|title=Disappointing growth, suffering tourism |date=2016-08-03|newspaper=Understand France|language=en-US|access-date=2016-12-04}}</ref> and known as a nation of [[Open market operation|open markets]], regulatory efficiency, rule of law and limited governmental intervention.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.heritage.org/index/country/france|title=France Economy: Facts, Population, GDP, Unemployment, Business, Trade|publisher=Heritage Foundation|access-date=2016-12-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2116.html#fr|title=The World Factbook |publisher=Central Intelligence Agency|access-date=2016-12-04}}</ref> Paris hosted the [[2015 United Nations Climate Change Conference]] and Hollande's efforts to attract the [[2024 Summer Olympics]] to the city were successful.\n\nNotwithstanding, with unemployment up to 10% and domestic troubles<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.rfi.fr/france/20130506-why-francois-hollande-so-unpopular-france |title=Why is Fran\u00e7ois Hollande so unpopular in France?|date=2013-05-06|publisher=RFI|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-12-04}}</ref> over his tenure due to terrorism, he faced spikes and downturns in approval rates, ultimately making him the most unpopular French President under the [[French Fifth Republic|Fifth Republic]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/oct/29/francois-hollande-most-unpopular-president|title=Fran\u00e7ois Hollande becomes most unpopular French president ever|last=Chrisafis|first=Angelique|date=2013-10-29|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=2016-12-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2016/07/05/nearly-90-percent-of-the-french-now-disapprove-of-their-president/|title=Nearly 90 percent of the French now disapprove of their president|website=Washington Post|access-date=2016-12-04}}</ref> On 1 December 2016, he announced he would not seek re-election in the [[2017 French presidential election]], for which [[Opinion polling for the 2017 French presidential election|polls]] announced his defeat in the first round.\n\n==Early life and education==\nFran\u00e7ois Hollande was born on 12 August 1954 in [[Rouen]].<ref name=\"dob\">{{cite web|title=Fran\u00e7ois HOLLANDE {{!}} History of parliamentary service {{!}} MEPs {{!}} European Parliament|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meps/en/4285/FRANCOIS_HOLLANDE_home.html|website=www.europarl.europa.eu|accessdate=13 April 2017|language=en}}</ref> His mother, Nicole Fr\u00e9d\u00e9rique Marguerite Tribert (1927\u20132009),<ref>{{cite web|title=Nicole Tribert, sa m\u00e8re - Fran\u00e7ois Hollande et les femmes de sa vie - Elle|url=http://www.elle.fr/Societe/L-actu-en-images/Francois-Hollande-et-les-femmes-de-sa-vie/Nicole-Tribert-sa-mere|website=www.elle.fr|accessdate=13 April 2017|language=fr-FR}}</ref> was a [[social worker]], and his father, Georges Gustave Hollande (born 1923<ref>{{cite news|language=fr|url=http://www.charentelibre.fr/2012/05/08/georges-hollande-sarkozy-a-fait-un-cadeau-empoisonne-a-mon-fils,1094053.php|title=Georges Hollande: \"Sarkozy a fait un cadeau empoisonn\u00e9 \u00e0 mon fils\"|newspaper=Charente libre|agency=AFP|date=8 May 2012|accessdate=1 July 2016}}</ref>), is a retired [[Otolaryngology|ear, nose, and throat doctor]] who \"ran for local election on a [[History of far-right movements in France|far right]] ticket in 1959.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Angelique Chrisafis in Le Bourget |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/jan/22/francois-hollande-socialist-french-elections |title=Francois Hollande stages first major rally in 2012 French presidential race &#124; World news |work=The Guardian |accessdate=6 May 2012 |location=London |date=22 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/oct/16/french-presidential-election-sarkozy-hollande | location=London |work=The Guardian | first1=Kim | last1=Willsher | title=French presidential election: Nicolas Sarkozy v Fran\u00e7ois Hollande | date=16 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/election-presidentielle-2012/en-images-francois-hollande-une-carriere-au-parti-socialiste-17-10-2011-1657616.php |title=EN IMAGES. Fran\u00e7ois Hollande, une carri\u00e8re au parti socialiste&nbsp;\u2013 Presidentielle 2012 |publisher=leParisien.fr |language=French|accessdate=3 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Email Us |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/weekend/2012/0421/1224315001448.html |title=We all know Sarko, but who's the other guy? |work=The Irish Times |date=21 April 2012 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/europe/2012/02/hollande-france-french-sarkozy |title=The NS Profile: Fran\u00e7ois Hollande |work=New Statesman |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/apr/18/francois-hollande-sarkozy-nemesis|title=Fran\u00e7ois Hollande: from marshmallow man to Sarkozy's nemesis? |first=Angelique |last=Chrisafis|newspaper=The Guardian|date=18 April 2012|accessdate=1 July 2016}}</ref> The name \"Hollande\" meant \"one originally from [[Holland]]\" \u2013 it is mostly found in Hollande's ancestral land, [[Hauts-de-France]], and it is speculated to be [[Dutch language|Dutch]] in origin. The earliest known member of the Hollande family lived circa 1569 near [[Plouvain]], working as a [[miller]].<ref>Luc Antonini, L'ascendance des candidats, dans G\u00e9n\u00e9alogie Magazine Hors-s\u00e9rie no 318-319, octobre-novembre 2011, p. 13</ref><ref>Serge Raffy, Le Pr\u00e9sident, Fran\u00e7ois Hollande, itin\u00e9raire secret, nouvelle \u00e9dition revue et augment\u00e9e, A. Fayard/Pluriel, 2012</ref>\n\nWhen Hollande was thirteen, the family moved to [[Neuilly-sur-Seine]], a highly exclusive suburb of Paris.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thomaswhite.com/global-perspectives/francois-hollande-president-france/ |title=Global Players: Francois Hollande &#124; Thomas White International |publisher=Thomaswhite.com |accessdate=15 May 2012}}</ref> He attended Saint-Jean-Baptiste-de-la-Salle boarding school, a private Catholic school in Rouen, the [[Lyc\u00e9e Pasteur (Neuilly-sur-Seine)|Lyc\u00e9e Pasteur]], in Neuilly-sur-Seine, receiving his baccalaureate in 1972 then graduated with a bachelor's degree in Law from [[Panth\u00e9on-Assas University]]. Hollande studied at [[HEC Paris]], graduated in 1975, and then attended the [[Institut d'\u00e9tudes politiques de Paris]] and the [[\u00c9cole nationale d'administration]] (ENA). He did his military service in the French Army in 1977.<ref>{{cite web|title=Francois Hollande Fast Facts|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/12/21/world/europe/francois-hollande---fast-facts/index.html|website=CNN.com|publisher=CNN|accessdate=14 July 2017}}</ref> He graduated from the ENA in 1980<ref>{{cite news|author= |url=http://www.economist.com/node/21549976 |title=The French elite: Old school ties |work=The Economist |accessdate=6 May 2012 |date=10 March 2012}}</ref> and chose to enter the prestigious [[Cour des comptes]].\n\nHollande lived in the United States in the summer of 1974 as a university student.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/15/magazine/the-soft-middle-of-francois-hollande.html|title=The Soft Middle of Fran\u00e7ois Hollande|last=Erlanger|first=Steven|date=15 April 2012|work=The New York Times|page=50|accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> Immediately after graduation, he was employed as a councillor in the [[Court of Audit of France|Court of Audit]].\n\n==Early political career==\nFive years after volunteering as a student to work for [[Fran\u00e7ois Mitterrand]]'s ultimately unsuccessful campaign in the [[1974 French presidential election|1974 presidential election]], Hollande joined the [[Socialist Party (France)|Socialist Party]]. He was quickly spotted by [[Jacques Attali]], a senior adviser to Mitterrand, who arranged for Hollande to run in [[1981 French legislative election|legislative election of 1981]] in [[Corr\u00e8ze]] against future President [[Jacques Chirac]], who was then the leader of the [[Rally for the Republic]], a [[Neo-Gaullist]] party. Hollande lost to Chirac in the first round.\n\nHe went on to become a special advisor to newly elected President Mitterrand, before serving as a staffer for [[Max Gallo]], the government's spokesman. After becoming a municipal [[councillor]] for [[Ussel, Corr\u00e8ze|Ussel]] in 1983, he contested Corr\u00e8ze for a second time in [[1988 French legislative election|1988]], this time being elected to the [[French National Assembly|National Assembly]]. Hollande lost his bid for re-election to the Assembly in the so-called \"blue wave\" of the [[1993 French legislative election|1993 election]], described as such due to the number of seats gained by the Right at the expense of the Socialist Party.\n\n===First Secretary of the Socialist Party (1997\u20132008)===\n[[File:Fran\u00e7ois Hollande2.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Fran\u00e7ois Hollande in 2005]]\nAs the end of Mitterrand's term in office approached, the Socialist Party was torn by a struggle of internal factions, each seeking to influence the direction of the party. Hollande pleaded for reconciliation and for the party to unite behind [[Jacques Delors]], the [[President of the European Commission]], but Delors renounced his ambitions to run for the French presidency in [[1995 French presidential election|1995]]. Former party leader [[Lionel Jospin]] resumed his position, and selected Hollande to become the official party spokesman. Hollande went on to contest Corr\u00e8ze once again in [[1997 French legislative election|1997]], successfully returning to the National Assembly.\n\nThat same year, Jospin became the [[Prime Minister of France]], and Hollande won the election for his successor as [[First Secretary of the French Socialist Party|First Secretary]] of the party, a position he would hold for eleven years. Because of the very strong position of the Socialist Party within the [[French government]] during this period, Hollande's position led some to refer to him the \"Vice Prime Minister\". Hollande would go on to be elected [[Mayor (France)|mayor]] of [[Tulle]] in 2001, an office he would hold for the next seven years.\n\nThe immediate resignation of Jospin from politics following his shock defeat by far-right candidate [[Jean-Marie Le Pen]] in the first round of the [[2002 French presidential election|2002 presidential election]] forced Hollande to become the public face of the party for the [[2002 French legislative election|2002 legislative election]]. Although he managed to limit defeats and was re-elected in [[Corr\u00e8ze's 1st Constituency|his own constituency]], the Socialists lost nationally. In order to prepare for the 2003 party congress in [[Dijon]], he obtained the support of many notable personalities of the party and was re-elected first secretary against opposition from left-wing factions.\n\nAfter the triumph of the Left in the [[2004 French regional elections|2004 regional elections]], Hollande was cited as a potential presidential candidate, but the Socialists were divided on the [[European Constitution]], and Hollande's support for the ill-fated \"Yes\" position in the [[2005 French European Constitution referendum|French referendum on the European constitution]] caused friction within the party. Although Hollande was re-elected as first secretary at the [[Le Mans Congress]] in 2005, his authority over the party began to decline. Eventually his domestic partner, [[S\u00e9gol\u00e8ne Royal]], was chosen to represent the party in the [[2007 French presidential election|2007 presidential election]], where she would lose to [[Nicolas Sarkozy]].\n\nHollande was widely blamed for the poor performances of the Socialist Party in the [[2007 French legislative election|2007 elections]], and he announced that he would not seek another term as First Secretary. Hollande publicly declared his support for [[Bertrand Delano\u00eb]], the [[mayor of Paris]], but it was [[Martine Aubry]] who would go on to win the race to succeed him in 2008. Hollande was next elected to replace [[Jean-Pierre Dupont]] as the president of the [[Corr\u00e8ze General Council|General Council of Corr\u00e8ze]] in April 2008, and won re-election in 2011.\n\n===2012 presidential campaign===\n{{Main|Fran\u00e7ois Hollande presidential campaign, 2012}}\n{{See also|French presidential election, 2012}}\nHollande announced in early 2011 that he would be a candidate in the upcoming [[French Socialist Party presidential primary, 2011|primary election]] to select the Socialist and [[Radical Left Party]] presidential nominee.<ref>{{cite news|last=Albinet|first=Alain|title=L'appel de Tulle de Fran\u00e7ois Hollande|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/politique/article/2011/03/31/l-appel-de-tulle-de-francois-hollande_1501495_823448.html|accessdate=29 June 2011|newspaper=[[Le Monde]]|date=31 March 2011|language=French}}</ref> The primary marked the first time that both parties had held an open primary to select a joint nominee at the same time. He initially trailed the front-runner, former finance minister and [[International Monetary Fund]] managing director [[Dominique Strauss-Kahn]]. Following Strauss-Kahn's [[Dominique Strauss-Kahn sexual assault case|arrest on suspicion of sexual assault]] in New York City in May 2011, Hollande began to lead the opinion polls, and his position as front-runner was established just as Strauss-Kahn declared that he would no longer seek the nomination. After a series of televised debates with other candidates throughout September, Hollande topped the ballot in the first round held on 9 October with 39% of the vote. He did not, however, gain the 50% required to avoid a [[run-off election]], and was obliged to enter a second ballot against [[Martine Aubry]], who had come in second with 30% of the vote.\n\nThe second ballot took place on 16 October 2011. Hollande won with 56% of the vote to Aubry's 43% and thus became the official Socialist and Radical Left Party candidate for the [[2012 French presidential election|2012 presidential election]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=French Unions in National Strike on Pensions |first=Steven |last=Erlanger |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/08/world/europe/08france.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=7 September 2010 |page=A4 |accessdate=4 December 2010 |quote=[Socialist party leader Martine] Aubry has presidential ambitions... Her rivals included the former leader of the party, Fran\u00e7ois Hollande....}}</ref> All his main opponents in the primary \u2013 Aubry, S\u00e9gol\u00e8ne Royal, [[Arnaud Montebourg]], and [[Manuel Valls]] \u2013 pledged their support to him for the general election.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Hollande to run for presidency for French left |first=Brian |last=Love |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/10/16/us-france-election-idUSTRE79F02T20111016 |agency=Reuters |date=16 September 2011 |accessdate=16 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Hollande 146.JPG|thumb|left|Hollande campaigning in [[Reims]], 2012]]\nHollande's presidential campaign was managed by [[Pierre Moscovici]] and [[St\u00e9phane Le Foll]], a member of Parliament and [[Member of the European Parliament]] respectively.<ref>{{cite web|last=Botella|first=Bruno|title=Fran\u00e7ois Hollande recrute deux pr\u00e9fets pour sa campagne|url=http://nominations.acteurspublics.com/focus/16-11-11/francois-hollande-recrute-deux-prefets-pour-sa-campagne|publisher=acteurs publics|accessdate=18 February 2012|language=fr|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111118004941/http://nominations.acteurspublics.com/focus/16-11-11/francois-hollande-recrute-deux-prefets-pour-sa-campagne|archivedate=18 November 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Hollande launched his campaign officially with a rally and major speech at [[Le Bourget]] on 22 January 2012 in front of 25,000 people.<ref name=hollandebourgetnyt>{{cite news|last=Erlanger|first=Steven|title=Fran\u00e7ois Hollande, Challenging Sarkozy, Calls for Change|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/23/world/europe/francois-hollande-challenging-sarkozy-calls-for-change.html|accessdate=18 February 2012|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=22 January 2012}}</ref><ref name=hollandebourgethp>{{cite news|last=Clavel|first=Geoffroy|title=Fran\u00e7ois Hollande, French Presidential Candidate, Says 'Finance' Is His Adversary|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/01/23/francois-hollande-tk_n_1222529.html|accessdate=18 February 2012|newspaper=[[Huffington Post]]|date=22 January 2012}}</ref> The main themes of his speech were equality and the regulation of finance, both of which he promised to make a key part of his campaign.<ref name=hollandebourgethp />\n\nOn 26 January, he outlined a full list of policies in a manifesto containing 60 propositions, including the separation of retail activities from riskier investment-banking businesses; raising taxes on big corporations, banks and the wealthy; creating 60,000 teaching jobs; bringing the official retirement age back down to 60 from 62; creating subsidised jobs in areas of high unemployment for the young; promoting more industry in France by creating a public investment bank; granting marriage and adoption rights to same-sex couples; and pulling French troops out of Afghanistan in 2012.<ref name=hollande26nyt>{{cite news|last=Erlanger|first=Steven|title=Sarkozy's Main Rival Offers Proposals for Lifting France's Economy|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/27/world/europe/in-france-francois-hollande-offers-plan-to-revive-economy.html?_r=1|accessdate=18 February 2012|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=26 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Presidential program&nbsp;\u2013 Fran\u00e7ois Hollande|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/79434607/Projet-Presidentiel-Francois-Hollande|accessdate=18 February 2012}}</ref> On 9 February, he detailed his policies specifically relating to education in a major speech in [[Orl\u00e9ans]].<ref>{{cite news|language=French|last= Laubacher|first=Paul|title=\u00c9ducation : Fran\u00e7ois Hollande fait de l'\u00e9cole primaire une priorit\u00e9|newspaper=[[Le Nouvel Observateur]]|date=10 February 2013|url=http://tempsreel.nouvelobs.com/election-presidentielle-2012/20120210.OBS1055/education-francois-hollande-fait-de-l-ecole-primaire-une-priorite.html|accessdate=18 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nIncumbent President [[Nicolas Sarkozy]] announced on 15 February that he would run for a second and final term, strongly criticising the Socialist proposals and claiming that Hollande would bring about \"economic disaster within two days of taking office\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/politique/2009/07/08/01002-20090708ARTFIG00007-sarkozy-se-voit-a-l-elysee-pour-encore-sept-ans-et-demi-.php |title=Politique : Sarkozy se voit \u00e0 l'\u00c9lys\u00e9e pour encore \"sept ans et demi\" |work=Le Figaro |accessdate=14 April 2012}}</ref> Opinion polls showed a tight race between the two men in the first round of voting, with most polls showing Hollande comfortably ahead of Sarkozy in a hypothetical second round.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opinion-way.com/pdf/opinionway_fiducial_pour_radio_classique_les_echos_vague_4_-_mars_2012.pdf |title=4 March 2012&nbsp;\u2013 Opinion Way |accessdate=19 April 2012}}</ref> The first round of the presidential election was held on 22 April. Fran\u00e7ois Hollande came in first place with 28.63% of the vote, and faced Nicolas Sarkozy in a run-off.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.france24.com/en/election-resultats |title=Elections Pr\u00e9sidentielle R\u00e9sultats |publisher=FRANCE 24 |date=22 April 2012 |accessdate=6 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120506074514/http://www.france24.com/en/election-resultats |archivedate=6 May 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> In the second round of voting on 6 May 2012, Hollande was elected with 51.6% of the vote.<ref name=\"france1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.france24.com/en/france/2min/20120506-france-socialist-hollande-wins-presidential-election-sarkozy |title=Socialist Hollande triumphs in French presidential poll&nbsp;\u2013 FRENCH ELECTIONS 2012 |publisher=FRANCE 24 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==President of France (2012\u20132017)==\n{{See also|Presidency of Fran\u00e7ois Hollande}}\n[[File:PR-2012-05-15 IMG 1620.jpg|thumb|Hollande (right) and outgoing President [[Nicolas Sarkozy]] at [[\u00c9lys\u00e9e Palace]] on inauguration day, 15 May 2012]]\n[[File:Francois Hollande Carcassonne-1118.jpg|thumb|Hollande during a meeting in [[Carcassonne]] in May 2015]]\nHollande was inaugurated on 15 May 2012, and shortly afterwards appointed [[Jean-Marc Ayrault]] to be his [[Prime Minister of France|Prime Minister]]. He was the first Socialist Party president since Fran\u00e7ois Mitterrand left office in 1995. The President of the French Republic is one of the two [[Co-Princes of Andorra|joint heads of state]] of the Principality of [[Andorra]]. Hollande hosted a visit from [[Antoni Mart\u00ed]], [[List of heads of government of Andorra|head of the government]], and [[Vicen\u00e7 Mateu Zamora]], leader of the [[General Council of Andorra|parliament]].<ref>[http://www.20minutes.fr/ledirect/977281/francois-hollande-co-prince-andorre-recoit-responsables-principaute \"Fran\u00e7ois Hollande, co-prince d'Andorre, re\u00e7oit des responsables de la principaut\u00e9\"], ''20 minutes'', 26 July 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.ambafrance-ad.org/Entretien-du-President-de-la \"Entretien du Pr\u00e9sident de la R\u00e9publique, M. Fran\u00e7ois Hollande avec MM. Marti et Mateu, Chef du Gouvernement et Syndic G\u00e9n\u00e9ral de la Principaut\u00e9 d\u2019Andorre\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140709201601/http://www.ambafrance-ad.org/Entretien-du-President-de-la |date=9 July 2014 }}, French embassy to Andorra, 30 July 2012</ref>\n\nHe also appointed [[Beno\u00eet Puga]] to be the military's chief of staff, [[Pierre-Ren\u00e9 Lemas]] as his general secretary and Pierre Besnard as his Head of Cabinet.<ref name=\"cabinet\">[http://www.elysee.fr/president/la-presidence/le-fonctionnement-de-la-presidence/le-cabinet-du-president-de-la-republique/le-cabinet-du-president-de-la-republique.13214.html Le cabinet du Pr\u00e9sident de la R\u00e9publique] elysee.fr 15 May 2012</ref> Hollande's full Council of Ministers became the first ever in France to show gender parity, with 17 men and 17 women, and each member was required to sign a new \"code of ethics\" that placed significant restrictions on their conduct and compensation, above that of existing law.<ref name=\"LeParisien17May2012\">{{Cite news|title=France: Hollande r\u00e9unit son gouvernement, baisse son salaire de 30%|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/flash-actualite-monde/france-hollande-reunit-son-gouvernement-baisse-son-salaire-de-30-17-05-2012-2004884.php|accessdate=2 February 2013|newspaper=[[Le Parisien]]|date=17 May 2012}}</ref> The first measure enacted by the new government was to lower the salaries of the President, the Prime Minister, and other members of the government by 30%.<ref name=\"LeParisien17May2012\" />\n\n===Budget===\nHollande's economic policies are wide-ranging, including supporting the creation of a European [[credit rating agency]], the separation of lending and investment in banks, reducing the share of electricity generated by [[nuclear power in France]] from 75 to 50% in favour of [[renewable energy]] sources, merging [[income tax]] and the [[Taxation in France|General Social Contribution (CSG)]], creating an additional 45% for additional income of 150,000 euros, capping tax loopholes at a maximum of \u20ac10,000 per year, and questioning the relief [[solidarity tax on wealth]] (ISF, ''Imp\u00f4t de Solidarit\u00e9 sur la Fortune'') measure that should bring \u20ac29 billion in additional revenue. Hollande also signalled his intent to implement a 75% income tax rate on revenue earned above 1,000,000 euros per year, to generate the provision of development funds for deprived suburbs, and to return to a deficit of zero percent of GDP by 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/france/9042741/Francois-Hollande-outlines-manifesto-for-French-presidency-challenge.html |title=Fran\u00e7ois Hollande outlines manifesto for French presidency challenge|work=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=6 May 2012 |location=London |first=Henry |last=Samuel |date=26 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=Le Figaro |url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-eco/2012/01/26/97002-20120126FILWWW00727-hollande-equilibre-impossible-sans-croissance.php |title=\"2% de croissance\": Hollande s'explique |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> The tax plan proved controversial, with courts ruling it unconstitutional in 2012, only to then take the opposite position on a redrafted version in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last=Fouquet |first=Helene |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-12-29/french-court-says-75-tax-rate-on-wealthy-is-unconstitutional.html |title=French Court Says 75% Tax Rate on the Rich Is Unconstitutional |work=Bloomberg |date=29 December 2012 |accessdate=16 June 2013}}{{Subscription required}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Petroff |first=Alanna |url=http://money.cnn.com/2013/12/30/news/economy/french-tax-75/ |title=France's 75% 'millionaire tax' to become law |work=Money.cnn.com |date=30 December 2013 |accessdate=26 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nHollande had also announced several reforms to education, pledging to recruit 60,000 new teachers, to create a study allowance and means-tested training, and to set up a mutually beneficial contract that would allow a generation of experienced employees and craftsmen to be the guardians and teachers of younger newly hired employees, thereby creating a total of 150,000 subsidized jobs. This was complemented by the promise of aid to [[Small and medium enterprises|SMEs]], with the creation of a public bank investment-oriented SME's, and a reduction of the [[corporate tax]] rate to 30% for medium corporations and 15% for small.\n\nHollande's government has announced plans to construct 500,000 public homes per year, including 150,000 [[Public housing in France|social houses]], funded by a doubling of the ceiling of the [[Passbook|A passbook]], the [[Regions of France|region]] making available its [[local government#France|local government]] land within five years. In accordance with long-standing Socialist Party policy, Hollande has announced that the [[retirement age]] will revert to 60, for those who have [[Pensions in France|contributed]] for more than 41 years.\n\n===Marriage and adoption for same-sex couples===\n{{Further|Law 2013-404}}\nHollande has also announced his personal support for [[Same-sex marriage in France|same-sex marriage]] and [[LGBT adoption|adoption for LGBT couples]], and outlined plans to pursue the issue in early 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.queerty.com/unpopular-french-president-nicolas-sarkozy-desperately-woos-gay-rights-20120330/ |title=Unpopular French President Nicolas Sarkozy Desperately Woos Les Gais |publisher=Queerty.com |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> In July 2012, Prime Minister [[Jean-Marc Ayrault]] announced that \"In the first half of 2013, the right to marriage and adoption will be open to all couples, without discrimination\", confirming this election promise by Hollande.<ref>[http://www.france24.com/en/20120703-gay-marriage-adoption-allowed-france-2013 ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120707010052/http://www.france24.com/en/20120703-gay-marriage-adoption-allowed-france-2013 |date=7 July 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=Le Figaro |url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/actualite-france/2012/07/03/01016-20120703ARTFIG00869-le-mariage-et-l-adoption-homosexuels-pour-debut-2013.php |title=Le mariage et l'adoption homosexuels pour d\u00e9but 2013 |accessdate=23 October 2012}}</ref>\n[[File:Fran\u00e7ois Hollande Official Portrait.jpg|thumb|Official Portrait of Hollande]]\nThe bill to legalize same-sex marriage, known as Bill no. 344, was introduced to the [[National Assembly of France]] on 7 November 2012. On 12 February 2013, the National Assembly approved the bill in a 329\u2013229 vote.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} ''[http://www.leparisien.fr/politique/loi-sur-le-mariage-pour-tous-les-deputes-adoptent-l-article-1-02-02-2013-2534345.php Loi sur le mariage pour tous : les d\u00e9put\u00e9s adoptent l'article 1].'' Retrieved 2 February 2013.</ref> The Right-wing opposed the bill. The [[Senate (France)|Senate]] approved the full bill with a 171\u2013165 majority on 12 April with minor amendments. On 23 April, the National Assembly approved the amended bill, in a 331\u2013225 vote, and following approval of the law by the [[Constitutional Council of France]], it was signed into law by President Hollande on 18 May 2013, with the first same-sex weddings under the law taking place eleven days later.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.france24.com/en/20130517-france-constitutional-court-council-approves-gay-marriage-bill |title=French constitutional court approves gay-marriage bill |publisher=France 24 |date=17 May 2013 |accessdate=16 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130613034731/http://www.france24.com/en/20130517-france-constitutional-court-council-approves-gay-marriage-bill |archive-date=13 June 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Labour reform===\n[[File:2016-03-09 11-35-56 manif-belfort.jpg|left|thumb|Demonstration against Hollande's labour reform in [[Belfort]], 2016]]\nAs President, Hollande pursued labour reform to make France more competitive internationally. Legislation was introduced in late 2012 and after much debate passed the French lower and upper house in May 2013. The bill includes measures such as making it easier for workers to change jobs and for companies to fire employees. One of the main measures of the bill allows companies to temporarily cut workers' salaries or hours during times of economic difficulty. This measure takes its inspiration from Germany, where furloughs have been credited with allowing companies to weather difficult times without resorting to massive layoffs. Layoffs in France are often challenged in courts and the cases can take years to resolve. Many companies cite the threat of lengthy court action&nbsp;\u2013 even more than any financial cost \u2013 as the most difficult part of doing business in France. The law shortens the time that employees have to contest a layoff and also lays out a scheme for severance pay. The government hopes this will help employees and companies reach agreement faster in contentious layoffs.<ref name=labour>{{cite news |url=https://news.yahoo.com/france-approves-major-labor-reform-package-160144959.html |title= France approves major labor reform package|author=Dilorenzo, Sarah|work=yahoo.com |date=14 May 2013 |accessdate=4 January 2014}}</ref>\n \nAnother key measure introduced are credits for training that follow employees throughout their career, regardless of where they work, and the right to take a leave of absence to work at another company. The law will also require all companies to offer and partially pay for supplemental health insurance. Lastly, the law also reforms unemployment insurance, so that someone out of work doesn't risk foregoing significant benefits when taking a job that might pay less than previous work or end up only being temporary. Under the new law, workers will be able to essentially put benefits on hold when they take temporary work, instead of seeing their benefits recalculated each time.<ref name=labour/>\n\n===Pension reform===\nAs President, Hollande pursued reform to the pension system in France. The process proved to be very contentious, with members of Parliament, Labor Unions, and general public all opposed. Mass protests and demonstrations occurred throughout Paris. Despite the opposition, the French Parliament did pass a reform in December 2013 aimed at plugging a pension deficit expected to reach 20.7 billion euros ($28.4 billion) by 2020 if nothing were to be done. Rather than raising the mandatory retirement age, as many economists had advised, Hollande pursued increases in contributions, leaving the retirement age untouched. The reform had a rough ride in parliament, being rejected twice by the Senate, where Hollande's Socialist Party has a slim majority, before it won sufficient backing in a final vote before the lower house of parliament. French private sector workers will see the size and duration of their pension contributions increase only modestly under the reform while their retirement benefits are largely untouched.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://au.news.yahoo.com/world/a/20393182/french-parliament-approves-pension-reform/ |title=French parliament approves pension reform |agency=Reuters |date=19 December 2013 |accessdate=4 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140104203944/http://au.news.yahoo.com/world/a/20393182/french-parliament-approves-pension-reform/ |archivedate=4 January 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n===Foreign affairs===\n{{see also|List of presidential trips made by Fran\u00e7ois Hollande}}\n[[File:Francois Hollande Bastille Day 2013 Paris t101747.jpg|thumb|Hollande reviewing troops during the 2013 [[Bastille Day military parade]]]]\nAs President, Hollande promised an early withdrawal of French combat troops present in Afghanistan in 2012.<ref name=guardianAC1/><ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|last=Fouquet |first=Helene |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-01-26/sarkozy-rival-hollande-may-seek-bank-split-in-election-platform.html |title=Socialist Hollande Pledges Tax Breaks End, Eased Pension Measure |publisher=Bloomberg |date=26 January 2012 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}{{Subscription required}}</ref> He also pledged to conclude a new contract of [[France\u2013Germany relations|Franco-German partnership]], advocating the adoption of a [[European Directive|Directive]] on the protection of public services. Hollande has proposed \"an acceleration of the establishment of a Franco-German civic service, the creation of a Franco-German research office, the creation of a Franco-German industrial fund to finance common competitiveness clusters, and the establishment of a common military headquarters\".<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|author=EurActiv.com, based on reporting by EurActiv.fr |url=http://www.euractiv.com/elections/fran-ois-hollande-european-new-deal-news-511108 |title=Fran\u00e7ois Hollande: Towards a European 'New Deal'? |publisher=EurActiv |accessdate=6 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301120453/http://www.euractiv.com/elections/fran-ois-hollande-european-new-deal-news-511108 |archivedate=1 March 2012 }}</ref> As well as this, Hollande has expressed a wish to \"combine the positions of the presidents of the [[European Commission]] and of the [[European Council]] (currently held by [[Jos\u00e9 Manuel Barroso]] and [[Herman Van Rompuy]] respectively) into a single office [...] and that it should be directly chosen\" by the [[Member of the European Parliament|members of the European Parliament]].<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n[[File:Barack Obama and Fran\u00e7ois Hollande on board Air Force One February 2014.jpg|thumb|Hollande and [[Barack Obama]] on board [[Air Force One]], 10 February 2014]]\nOn 11 January 2013, Hollande authorised the execution of [[Operation Serval]], which aimed to curtail the activities of Islamist extremists in the north of Mali.<ref name=guardianAC1>{{cite news|last=Chrisafis|first=Ang\u00e9lique|title=Mali: high stakes in 'Hollande's war'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jan/13/mali-high-stakes-francois-hollande|accessdate=2 February 2013|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|location=London|date=13 January 2013}}</ref> The intervention was popularly supported in Mali, as Hollande promised that his government would do all it could to \"rebuild Mali\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Andrew Harding |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-21308310 |title=French President Hollande pledges to help rebuild Mali |work=BBC News|date=2 February 2013 |accessdate=16 June 2013}}</ref> During his one-day visit to [[Bamako]], Mali's capital, on 2 February 2013, he said that it was \"the most important day in [his] political life\".<ref name=effect>{{cite news|title=The Bamako Effect|url=https://www.economist.com/news/europe/21571450-will-frances-intervention-mali-make-fran%C3%A7ois-hollande-popular-home-bamako-effect|newspaper=The Economist|date=9 February 2013}}{{Subscription required}}</ref> In 2014, Hollande took some of these troops out of Mali and spread them over the rest of the Sahel under [[Operation Barkhane]], in an effort to curb jihadist militants.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-28298230 |title=France sets up anti-Islamist force in Africa's Sahel |work=BBC News |date=14 July 2014 |accessdate=26 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/02/11/politics/gallery/france-state-visit/index.html?hpt=po_c2 |title=French President visits America |publisher=CNN.com |date= |accessdate=26 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/02/11/politics/state-dinner/index.html?hpt=po_c2 |title=Politics with side of caviar: Obama welcomes Hollande at state dinner |publisher=CNN.com |date=12 February 2014 |accessdate=26 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/francois-hollande/10629639/Francois-Hollande-arrives-in-United-States-No-more-freedom-fries-as-Obama-rolls-out-red-carpet.html|title=Fran\u00e7ois Hollande arrives in United States: No more 'freedom fries' as Obama rolls out red carpet|date=10 February 2014|work=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|accessdate=13 February 2014}}</ref> \nOn 27 February 2014, Hollande was a special guest of honor in Abuja, received by Nigerian President [[Goodluck Jonathan]] in celebration of Nigeria's amalgamation in 1914, a 100-year anniversary.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://m.news24.com/nigeria/National/News/Security-issues-dominate-as-Frances-Hollande-visits-Nigeria-20140227-9 |title=Security issues dominate as France's Hollande visits Nigeria |work=M.news24.com |date=27 February 2014 |accessdate=26 August 2014}}</ref> In July 2014, Hollande expressed support for [[Israel]]'s right to defend itself during the [[2014 Israel\u2013Gaza conflict]], and told Israeli Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]], \"France strongly condemns these aggressions [by Hamas].\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/182721 |title=France, Germany 'Strongly Condemn' Rockets on Israel |work=Israel national news |date=9 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Normandy format talks in Minsk (February 2015) 03 cropped.jpeg|thumb|Leaders of Belarus, Russia, Germany, France, and Ukraine at the [[Minsk II]] summit, 11\u201312 February 2015]]\nIn September 2015, Hollande warned former [[Eastern Bloc]] countries against rejecting the [[European migrant crisis#Relocation and resettlement of asylum seekers|EU mandatory migrant quotas]], saying: \"Those who don't share our values, those who don't even want to respect those principles, need to start asking themselves questions about their place in the European Union\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/migrant-crisis-hungarian-pm-viktor-orban-proposes-eu-border-force-patrol-greek-frontier-1520934 |title=Migrant crisis: Hungarian PM Viktor Orban proposes EU border force to patrol Greek frontier |website=[[International Business Times]] |date=23 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nHollande supported the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen]],<ref>\"[http://www.france24.com/en/20150412-france-fabius-support-saudi-campaign-yemen-houthis France voices support for Saudi campaign in Yemen]\". France 24. 12 April 2015.</ref> re-supplying the Saudi military.<ref>[http://www.france24.com/en/20160823-arms-trade-france-yemen-saudi-arabia-att-treaty-human-rights Pressure mounts on Western powers to halt arms sales to Saudi Arabia]\". France 24. 23 August 2016.</ref> France authorised $18 billion (\u20ac16 billion) in arms sales to [[Saudi Arabia]] in 2015.<ref>\"[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-yemen-security-arms-idUSKCN10X1MM Arms sales to Saudi 'illicit' due to civilian deaths in Yemen: campaigners]\". Reuters. 22 August 2016.</ref>\n{{check quotation}}\nIn 2014, French bank [[BNP Paribas]] agreed to pay an $8.9 billion fine, the largest ever for violating [[United States sanctions against Iran|U.S. sanctions against Iran]] at that time.<ref>{{cite news |title=French bank fined for violating US sanctions |url=https://www.dw.com/en/french-bank-fined-for-violating-us-sanctions/a-18792404 |work=Deutsche Welle |date=October 20, 2015}}</ref> In October 2016, Hollande said: \"When the (European) Commission goes after Google or digital giants which do not pay the taxes they should in Europe, America takes offence. And yet, they quite shamelessly demand 8 billion from BNP or 5 billion from Deutsche Bank.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=France's Hollande criticises huge U.S. fines against corporate Europe |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/france-politics-usa-idUSL8N1CI3B9 |work=Reuters |date=12 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Approval ratings===\nAn IFOP poll released in April 2014 showed that Hollande's approval rating had dropped five points since the previous month of March to 18%, dipping below his earlier low of 20% in February during the same year.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ifop.fr/media/poll/2601-1-study_file.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=12 August 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826115108/http://www.ifop.fr/media/poll/2601-1-study_file.pdf |archive-date=26 August 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In November 2014, his approval rating reached a new low of 12%, according to a YouGov poll.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sage|first1=Alexandria|title=Hollande popularity plumbs new low in mid-term French poll|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/11/06/us-france-hollande-idUSKBN0IQ14R20141106|accessdate=7 November 2014|agency=Reuters|date=6 November 2014}}</ref> Following the [[Charlie Hebdo shooting|''Charlie Hebdo'' shooting]] in January 2015, however, approval for Hollande increased dramatically, reaching 40% according to an IFOP poll two weeks after the attack,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/french-presidents-popularity-rating-doubles-following-charlie-hebdo-attacks-300518|title=French President's Popularity Rating Doubles Following Paris Attacks|first=Damien|last=Sharkov|date=19 January 2015|access-date=11 February 2015|newspaper=Newsweek}}</ref> though an Ipsos-Le Point survey in early February showed his rating declining back to 30%.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2015/02/09/uk-france-poll-hollande-idUKKBN0LD2CH20150209|title=Hollande, Valls approval ratings drop - poll|agency=Reuters|date=9 February 2015|accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nHollande is the most unpopular president of the [[French Fifth Republic]]. In September 2014, his approval rating was down to 13% according to an IFOP/JDD survey, making him the first French leader in modern times to ever break the 20% threshold.<ref name=\n\"LeMondeSep2014\">{{cite news|language=fr |url=http://www.lemonde.fr/les-decodeurs/article/2014/09/04/francois-hollande-devient-officiellement-le-president-le-plus-impopulaire_4482376_4355770.html |title=Fran\u00e7ois Hollande devient le pr\u00e9sident le plus impopulaire de la Ve R\u00e9publique |newspaper=[[Le Monde]]|date=4 September 2014|accessdate= 20 July 2016}}</ref> One year before the end of his mandate, in April 2016, his approval rating was at 14%, and surveys predicted that if he were to run for a second term, he would be defeated in the first round of the [[2017 French presidential election|2017 presidential elections]].<ref>{{cite news|language=fr |url=http://lci.tf1.fr/politique/a-un-an-de-la-presidentielle-hollande-president-le-plus-impopulaire-8735780.html |title=14% contre 28% pour Sarkozy \u00e0 la m\u00eame \u00e9poque : Hollande pr\u00e9sident le plus impopulaire de la Ve R\u00e9publique |publisher=[[TF1|My TF1 News]] |date=23 April 2016 |accessdate=20 July 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710171056/http://lci.tf1.fr/politique/a-un-an-de-la-presidentielle-hollande-president-le-plus-impopulaire-8735780.html |archivedate=10 July 2016 |df=dmy }}</ref> By November 2016, Hollande's approval rating was just 4%.<ref>[https://foreignpolicy.com/2016/11/02/mon-dieu-francois-hollandes-approval-rating-is-at-four-percent/ \"Mon Dieu, Fran\u00e7ois Hollande\u2019s Approval Rating Is at 4 Percent\"], Emily Tamkin. Foreign Policy. 2 November 2016. Accessed 18 January 2017</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Socialist rally Zenith 2007 05 29 n2.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Hollande with his former partner [[S\u00e9gol\u00e8ne Royal]], at a rally for the [[2007 French legislative election|2007 elections]]]]\nFor over thirty years, his [[domestic partnership|partner]] was fellow Socialist politician [[S\u00e9gol\u00e8ne Royal]], with whom he has four children: Thomas (1984), Cl\u00e9mence (1985), Julien (1987) and Flora (1992). In June 2007, just a month after Royal's defeat in the [[French presidential election of 2007]], the couple announced that they were separating.<ref>{{Cite news |title=French Socialists' First Couple Disclose a Parting of Ways |first=Elaine |last=Sciolino |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/19/world/europe/19france.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=19 June 2007 |page=A3 |accessdate=4 December 2010 }}</ref>\n\nA few months after his split from S\u00e9gol\u00e8ne Royal was announced, a French website published details of a relationship between Hollande and French journalist [[Val\u00e9rie Trierweiler]]. In November 2007, Trierweiler confirmed and openly discussed her relationship with Hollande in an interview with the French weekly ''[[T\u00e9l\u00e9 7 Jours]]''. She remained a reporter for the magazine ''[[Paris Match]]'', but ceased work on political stories. Trierweiler moved into the \u00c9lys\u00e9e Palace with Hollande when he became president and started to accompany him on official travel.<ref>\n[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-25680726 The women in Francois Hollande's life] [[BBC News]] 10 January 2014</ref>\n\nOn 25 January 2014, Hollande officially announced his separation from Val\u00e9rie Trierweiler<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europe1.fr/Politique/Francois-Hollande-annonce-sa-rupture-avec-Valerie-Trierweiler-1782209/ |title=Fran\u00e7ois Hollande annonce sa rupture avec Val\u00e9rie Trierweiler - val\u00e9rie trierweiler sur Europe1 |publisher=Europe1.fr |date=29 April 2014 |accessdate=26 August 2014}}</ref> after the tabloid magazine ''[[Closer (magazine)|Closer]]'' revealed his affair with actress [[Julie Gayet]].<ref name=\"Pressure Mounts Against President Hollande\">{{cite web | url=http://www.wwd.com/media-news/fashion-memopad/pressure-mounts-against-president-hollande-7361630?src=nl/mornReport/20140116 | title=Pressure Mounts Against President Hollande | work=Women's Wear Daily | date=16 January 2014 | accessdate=16 January 2014 | author=Alex Wynne and Laure Guilbault}}</ref> In September 2014, Trierweiler published a book about her time with Hollande titled ''Merci pour ce moment ([[Thank You for This Moment]]).'' The memoir claimed the president presented himself as disliking the rich, but in reality disliked the poor. The claim brought an angry reaction and rejection from Hollande, who said he had spent his life dedicated to the under-privileged.<ref name=\"HollandePoor\">{{cite news|title=Upset Hollande hits back at former girlfriend's accusations|url=http://www.parisnews.net/index.php/sid/225439693|date=5 September 2014|accessdate=7 September 2014|publisher=Paris News.Net}}</ref>\n\nHollande was raised [[Catholicism|Catholic]], but became an [[Agnosticism|agnostic]] later in life.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.directmatin.fr/article/27399|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130106181916/http://www.directmatin.fr/article/27399|url-status=dead|archive-date=6 January 2013|title=Prince et chanoine : les nouveaux m\u00e9tiers de Hollande|publisher=Direct Matin |accessdate=18 June 2012}}</ref> He now considers himself to be an [[atheist]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europe1.fr/Politique/Francois-Hollande-un-athee-tres-discret-1780573/|title=Fran\u00e7ois Hollande, un ath\u00e9e tr\u00e8s discret|last1=Duchemin |first1=R\u00e9mi|date=23 January 2014|website=Europe1.fr|publisher=Europe 1|accessdate= 13 July 2014|language=fr}}</ref> but still professes respect for all religious practices.<ref name=\"origines\">{{cite news | first = Olivia | last = Elka\u00efm | title = Fran\u00e7ois Hollande : des origines protestantes hollandaises | date = 5 April 2012 | url = http://www.lavie.fr/actualite/france/francois-hollande-des-origines-protestantes-hollandaises-04-05-2012-27124_4.php | work = [[La Vie]] | accessdate = 3 February 2013 | language = French}} (\"En d\u00e9cembre dernier, Fran\u00e7ois Hollande confiait \u00e0 La Vie : 'Je n'ai aucune pratique religieuse. Mais je respecte toutes les confessions. La mienne est de ne pas en avoir.'\")</ref>\n\n==Honours and decorations==\n===National honours===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:80px;\"| Ribbon bar !! Honour !! Date & Comment\n|-\n| [[File:Legion Honneur GC ribbon.svg|80px]]\n| [[Grand Cross]] of the National [[Chivalric order|Order]] of the [[Legion of Honour]]\n| 15 May 2012 \u2013 automatic upon taking presidential office\n|-\n| [[File:National Order of Merit Grand Cross Ribbon.png|80px]]\n| [[Grand Cross]] of the [[National Order of Merit (France)|National Order of Merit]]\n| 15 May 2012 \u2013 automatic upon taking presidential office\n|}\n\n===Foreign honours===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:80px;\"| Ribbon bar !! Country !! Honour !! Date\n|-\n| [[File:POL Order Or\u0142a Bia\u0142ego BAR.svg|80px]] || [[Poland]] || Knight of the [[Order of the White Eagle (Poland)|Order of the White Eagle]] || 16 November 2012<ref>[http://www.prezydent.pl/gfx/prezydent/pl/defaultaktualnosci/9/2367/1/1719111607.jpg Orders exchange between Polish and French Presidents (photo)] \u2013 prezydent.pl</ref><ref>[http://www.elysee.fr/president/root/bank_objects/T6-D51K9414.jpg Orders exchange between Polish and French Presidents (photo)]{{dead link|date=October 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} \u2013 Knight Grand Cross Order of Merit of the Italian Republic elysee.fr</ref>\n|-\n| [[File:ITA OMRI 2001 GC-GCord BAR.svg|80px]] || [[Italy]] || Knight Grand Cross with Collar of the [[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic]] || 21 November 2012<ref>{{in lang|it}} Italian Presidency website, [http://www.quirinale.it/elementi/Continua.aspx?tipo=Foto&key=25645 Exchange of decorations between President Napolitano and President Hollande]</ref>\n|-\n| [[File:Decoration_without_ribbon_-_en.svg|80px]] || [[Morocco]] || Grand Collar of the [[Order of Muhammad]] || 3 April 2013<ref>{{in lang|fr}} Maroc.ma, [http://www.maroc.ma/fr/activites-royales/sa-majest%C3%A9-le-roi-sentretient-avec-le-pr%C3%A9sident-fran%C3%A7ais]</ref>\n|-\n| [[File:Spange des K\u00f6nig-Abdulaziz-Ordens.png|80px]] || [[Saudi Arabia]] || Chain 