{"title_page": "Heartland Bank", "text_new": "{{Use New Zealand English|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{advert|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Heartland Bank Limited\n| logo = HB Logo.png\n| type = [[Publicly listed company]]\n| traded_as = {{NZX|HGH}}\n| fate = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| foundation = {{start date |df=yes|2011|1|5}}\n| key_people = Jeff Greenslade, CEO\n| founder = \n| defunct = \n| location_city = Auckland\n| location_country = [[New Zealand]]\n| area_served = New Zealand & Australia\n| industry = [[Financial Services]]\n| products = Savings & deposits, reverse mortgages, small business finance, motor vehicle finance, livestock finance\n| services = \n| revenue = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| aum = \n| assets = $4.0 billion\n| equity = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = more than 350\n| num_employees_year = 2018\n| parent = \n| divisions = \n| subsid = \n| homepage = {{url|http://www.heartland.co.nz/}}\n}}\n\n'''Heartland Bank''' is a New Zealand owned [[bank]] that was created in 2011 through the merging of four financial organisations to gain.Heartland was granted its bank registration by the Reserve Bank of New Zealand in 2012. <ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.interest.co.nz/bonds/62517/reserve-bank-confirms-banking-registration-building-society-heartland-nz |title=Reserve Bank confirms banking registration for building society Heartland NZ |date=17 December 2012|publisher=interest.co.nz }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/industries/4466114/Court-approves-heartland-bank-merger |title=Court approves 'heartland bank' merger |publisher=stuff.co.nz |date=16 December 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.odt.co.nz/news/business/227145/heartland-yet-consider-finance-arm |title=Heartland yet to consider finance arm |date=24 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.interest.co.nz/news/60869/heartland-nz-sees-funding-cost-premium-halve-expects-further-drop-if-it-successfully-secu |title=Heartland NZ sees funding cost premium halve |publisher=interest.co.nz |date=29 August 2012 }}</ref> It specialises in motor vehicle loans, reverse mortgages, small business finance, livestock finance, savings, investments and deposits.\n\nHeartland became a registered bank on in 2012 but its predecessors have had a long history in New Zealand with roots stretching back to 1875. \n\n==History==\n\n===Predecessors===\nIn 1875, the ''Ashburton Permanent Building & Investment Society'' was established, which subsequently merged with ''SMC Building Society'' and ''Loan & Building Society''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/loan-and-building-society-(ns)/news/article.cfm?o_id=102&objectid=10469262 |title=Canterbury Building Society to merge with Loan and Building |date=11 October 2007 |publisher=The New Zealand Herald}}</ref> Together they became ''CBS Canterbury''.\n\nSeparately ''Southern Cross Building Society'' opened in Auckland in 1923, it offered a similar range of financial services to its customers throughout the North Island.\n\nIn 1952, ''MARAC finance'' was established lending money to business to purchase commercial vehicles as the ''North Shore Rental Van Company''.  Over the next 55 years it grew to provide financing, lending and insurance services to businesses and individuals.\n\nLeading [[Stock and station agent|stock and station businesses]], [[Williams & Kettle]], [[Wrightson]], [[Pyne Gould Guinness]], and Reid Farmers which became [[PGG Wrightson]] established PGG Wrightson Finance (PWF) in the 1940s.  PWF provided financial services to its farming and rural clients.\n\nIn late 2010 a plan was hatched to bring together these four separate financial institutions to create a financial company with national coverage across New Zealand that had enough assets to become a bank.  On 5 January 2011, CBS Canterbury, Southern Cross Building Society and MARAC Finance Limited combined to become one organisation and on 31 August 2011, the Group acquired PGG Wrightson Finance.\n\n===Becoming a bank===\nHeartland was created from the merger of CBS Canterbury (Canterbury Building Society), Southern Cross, MARAC and PGG Wrightson Finance.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/BU1012/S00379/heartland-bank-gets-final-thumbs-up-from-depositors.htm |title=Heartland bank gets final thumbs up from depositors |date=10 December 2010 |publisher=scoop }}</ref>  The rationale for the merger was to create financial institution that had national coverage and enough assets and resources to get a full banking licence.\n\nOn 12 December 2012, the [[Reserve Bank of New Zealand]] announced that Heartland Building Society has been registered as a bank and the organisation changed its name to Heartland Bank. \n\n===Credit Rating===\nIn May 2013 ratings agency, [[Standard & Poor's]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.odt.co.nz/news/business/257380/small-banks-put-notice |title=Small banks put on notice |date=17 May 2013 |publisher=Otago Daily Times }}</ref> placed Heartland Bank, together with seven other small New Zealand financial institutions on a [[credit rating]] downgrade watch, citing potential risks from overexposure to New Zealand's highly inflated housing market. In October 2014, Heartland's rating was raised to BBB (outlook stable) in October 2014. <ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/business/news/article.cfm?c_id=3&objectid=11349854| title=Heartland's stronger asset quality, earnings earn Fitch upgrade| date=29 October 2014| publisher=NZ Herald}}</ref> In October 2015, Fitch, another credit ratings agency confirmed Heartland with a rating of BBB (Outlook stable), noting \"core asset quality to remain sound, benefiting from continued improvement in underwriting standards and good economic conditions\".<ref>{{cite press release| url=http://www.heartland.co.nz/_upload/news/Fitch%20Ratings%20release%20and%20report%20combined.pdf| title=Fitch Affirms Credit Rating for Heartland Bank| date=16 October 2015| publisher=Heartland Bank| access-date=31 December 2015| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160123102318/http://www.heartland.co.nz/_upload/news/Fitch%20Ratings%20release%20and%20report%20combined.pdf| archive-date=23 January 2016| url-status=dead}}</ref> In September 2018, Fitch affirmed Heartland's credit rating of BBB (outlook Stable) noting Heartland \"has achieved a leading niche franchise and some price-setting power, which resulted in a strong net interest margin\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shareholders.heartland.co.nz/media/1529/press-release_fitch-affirms-heartland-bank-limited-at-bbb.pdf|title=Fitch Press Release}}</ref>\n\n===Acquisitions and Partnerships===\nIn February 2014, Heartland moved into the [[Reverse Mortgage]] (or Home Equity Release) market through the purchase of Sentinel in New Zealand and Australian Seniors Finance in Australia.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/money/9722585/Heartland-buys-reverse-mortgage-firm| title=Heartland buys reverse mortgage firm| first=Richard| last=Meadows| publisher=Fairfax Media}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2014, Heartland purchased a 10% shareholding in [[peer-to-peer lending|peer-to-peer lender]] [[Harmoney |Harmoney Limited]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/business/news/article.cfm?c_id=3&objectid=11321019|title=Heartland buys into HarMoney| last=Adams| first=Christopher| date=9 September 2014| publisher=NZ Herald}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, Heartland partnered with Spotcap Australia, and online lender to small and medium-sized businesses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/business/88927020/online-lender-spotcap-partners-with-heartland-bank.html|title=Online lender Spotcap partners with Heartland Bank|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref>\n\n===Open for Business - Unsecured Small Business Loans===\nIn April 2016, Heartland launched an online platform, Open for Business, offering unsecured loans for small businesses.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/78667806/heartland-bank-boasts-the-fastest-loan-in-new-zealand|title=Heartland Bank boasts the fastest loan in New Zealand|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref>  An application through Open for Business can be completed in two to three minutes and the applicant receives an immediate decision.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/personal-finance/news/article.cfm?c_id=12&objectid=11857621|title=Heartland's big focus on small loans|last=tamsyn.parker@nzherald.co.nz|first=Tamsyn Parker Money Editor, NZ Herald|date=2017-05-16|work=NZ Herald|access-date=2018-10-06|language=en-NZ|issn=1170-0777}}</ref>\n\n===Savings & Investments===\nIn May 2018, Heartland's Direct Call Account received a 5-star rating from [[CANSTAR]] in its Flexible Saver and Regular Saver categories.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.canstar.co.nz/savings-accounts/make-savings-transaction-accounts-work/|title=Five-star savings and transaction accounts 2018 - Canstar|date=2018-05-29|work=Canstar|access-date=2018-10-06|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, Heartland launched a mobile app for its deposit customers to give them better control over their investments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/nz/app/heartland-mobile-app/id1401756383?mt=8|title=Heartland Mobile App|website=App\u00a0Store|language=en-AU|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/BU1809/S00225/heartland-releases-mobile-app-for-deposit-customers.htm|title=Heartland releases Mobile App for deposit customers  {{!}} Scoop News|website=www.scoop.co.nz|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, Heartland was named Canstar Bank of the Year \u2013 Savings.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.canstar.co.nz/savings-accounts/start-saving-honest-spending-heartland-advises/|title=Canstar Bank of the Year \u2013 Savings 2018: Heartland|date=2018-07-02|work=Canstar|access-date=2018-10-06|language=en-GB}}</ref> Canstar researched, analysed and compared 31 accounts from 11 providers for the annual ratings.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn April 2020, Heartland decided to not pass on interest rate reductions, after the Reserve bank dropped the OCR to a record low, as they looked to preserve their own profits, rather than looking after their customers.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.heartland.co.nz/}}\n\n{{New Zealand Building Societies}}\n{{NZ Banks |state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:Building societies of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Banks of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Ashburton, New Zealand]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use New Zealand English|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{advert|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Heartland Bank Limited\n| logo = HB Logo.png\n| type = [[Publicly listed company]]\n| traded_as = {{NZX|HGH}}\n| fate = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| foundation = {{start date |df=yes|2011|1|5}}\n| key_people = Jeff Greenslade, CEO\n| founder = \n| defunct = \n| location_city = Auckland\n| location_country = [[New Zealand]]\n| area_served = New Zealand & Australia\n| industry = [[Financial Services]]\n| products = Savings & deposits, reverse mortgages, small business finance, motor vehicle finance, livestock finance\n| services = \n| revenue = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| aum = \n| assets = $4.0 billion\n| equity = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = more than 350\n| num_employees_year = 2018\n| parent = \n| divisions = \n| subsid = \n| homepage = {{url|http://www.heartland.co.nz/}}\n}}\n\n'''Heartland Bank''' is a New Zealand owned [[bank]] that was created in 2011 through the merging of four financial organisations to gain.Heartland was granted its bank registration by the Reserve Bank of New Zealand in 2012. <ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.interest.co.nz/bonds/62517/reserve-bank-confirms-banking-registration-building-society-heartland-nz |title=Reserve Bank confirms banking registration for building society Heartland NZ |date=17 December 2012|publisher=interest.co.nz }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/industries/4466114/Court-approves-heartland-bank-merger |title=Court approves 'heartland bank' merger |publisher=stuff.co.nz |date=16 December 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.odt.co.nz/news/business/227145/heartland-yet-consider-finance-arm |title=Heartland yet to consider finance arm |date=24 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.interest.co.nz/news/60869/heartland-nz-sees-funding-cost-premium-halve-expects-further-drop-if-it-successfully-secu |title=Heartland NZ sees funding cost premium halve |publisher=interest.co.nz |date=29 August 2012 }}</ref> It specialises in motor vehicle loans, reverse mortgages, small business finance, livestock finance, savings, investments and deposits.\n\nHeartland became a registered bank on in 2012 but its predecessors have had a long history in New Zealand with roots stretching back to 1875. They continue to screw the average New Zealander with abhorrent interest rates to this day.\n\n==History==\n\n===Predecessors===\nIn 1875, the ''Ashburton Permanent Building & Investment Society'' was established, which subsequently merged with ''SMC Building Society'' and ''Loan & Building Society''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/loan-and-building-society-(ns)/news/article.cfm?o_id=102&objectid=10469262 |title=Canterbury Building Society to merge with Loan and Building |date=11 October 2007 |publisher=The New Zealand Herald}}</ref> Together they became ''CBS Canterbury''.\n\nSeparately ''Southern Cross Building Society'' opened in Auckland in 1923, it offered a similar range of financial services to its customers throughout the North Island.\n\nIn 1952, ''MARAC finance'' was established lending money to business to purchase commercial vehicles as the ''North Shore Rental Van Company''.  Over the next 55 years it grew to provide financing, lending and insurance services to businesses and individuals.\n\nLeading [[Stock and station agent|stock and station businesses]], [[Williams & Kettle]], [[Wrightson]], [[Pyne Gould Guinness]], and Reid Farmers which became [[PGG Wrightson]] established PGG Wrightson Finance (PWF) in the 1940s.  PWF provided financial services to its farming and rural clients.\n\nIn late 2010 a plan was hatched to bring together these four separate financial institutions to create a financial company with national coverage across New Zealand that had enough assets to become a bank.  On 5 January 2011, CBS Canterbury, Southern Cross Building Society and MARAC Finance Limited combined to become one organisation and on 31 August 2011, the Group acquired PGG Wrightson Finance.\n\n===Becoming a bank===\nHeartland was created from the merger of CBS Canterbury (Canterbury Building Society), Southern Cross, MARAC and PGG Wrightson Finance.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/BU1012/S00379/heartland-bank-gets-final-thumbs-up-from-depositors.htm |title=Heartland bank gets final thumbs up from depositors |date=10 December 2010 |publisher=scoop }}</ref>  The rationale for the merger was to create financial institution that had national coverage and enough assets and resources to get a full banking licence.\n\nOn 12 December 2012, the [[Reserve Bank of New Zealand]] announced that Heartland Building Society has been registered as a bank and the organisation changed its name to Heartland Bank. \n\n===Credit Rating===\nIn May 2013 ratings agency, [[Standard & Poor's]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.odt.co.nz/news/business/257380/small-banks-put-notice |title=Small banks put on notice |date=17 May 2013 |publisher=Otago Daily Times }}</ref> placed Heartland Bank, together with seven other small New Zealand financial institutions on a [[credit rating]] downgrade watch, citing potential risks from overexposure to New Zealand's highly inflated housing market. In October 2014, Heartland's rating was raised to BBB (outlook stable) in October 2014. <ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/business/news/article.cfm?c_id=3&objectid=11349854| title=Heartland's stronger asset quality, earnings earn Fitch upgrade| date=29 October 2014| publisher=NZ Herald}}</ref> In October 2015, Fitch, another credit ratings agency confirmed Heartland with a rating of BBB (Outlook stable), noting \"core asset quality to remain sound, benefiting from continued improvement in underwriting standards and good economic conditions\".<ref>{{cite press release| url=http://www.heartland.co.nz/_upload/news/Fitch%20Ratings%20release%20and%20report%20combined.pdf| title=Fitch Affirms Credit Rating for Heartland Bank| date=16 October 2015| publisher=Heartland Bank| access-date=31 December 2015| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160123102318/http://www.heartland.co.nz/_upload/news/Fitch%20Ratings%20release%20and%20report%20combined.pdf| archive-date=23 January 2016| url-status=dead}}</ref> In September 2018, Fitch affirmed Heartland's credit rating of BBB (outlook Stable) noting Heartland \"has achieved a leading niche franchise and some price-setting power, which resulted in a strong net interest margin\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shareholders.heartland.co.nz/media/1529/press-release_fitch-affirms-heartland-bank-limited-at-bbb.pdf|title=Fitch Press Release}}</ref>\n\n===Acquisitions and Partnerships===\nIn February 2014, Heartland moved into the [[Reverse Mortgage]] (or Home Equity Release) market through the purchase of Sentinel in New Zealand and Australian Seniors Finance in Australia.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/money/9722585/Heartland-buys-reverse-mortgage-firm| title=Heartland buys reverse mortgage firm| first=Richard| last=Meadows| publisher=Fairfax Media}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2014, Heartland purchased a 10% shareholding in [[peer-to-peer lending|peer-to-peer lender]] [[Harmoney |Harmoney Limited]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/business/news/article.cfm?c_id=3&objectid=11321019|title=Heartland buys into HarMoney| last=Adams| first=Christopher| date=9 September 2014| publisher=NZ Herald}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, Heartland partnered with Spotcap Australia, and online lender to small and medium-sized businesses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/business/88927020/online-lender-spotcap-partners-with-heartland-bank.html|title=Online lender Spotcap partners with Heartland Bank|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref>\n\n===Open for Business - Unsecured Small Business Loans===\nIn April 2016, Heartland launched an online platform, Open for Business, offering unsecured loans for small businesses.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/78667806/heartland-bank-boasts-the-fastest-loan-in-new-zealand|title=Heartland Bank boasts the fastest loan in New Zealand|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref>  An application through Open for Business can be completed in two to three minutes and the applicant receives an immediate decision.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/personal-finance/news/article.cfm?c_id=12&objectid=11857621|title=Heartland's big focus on small loans|last=tamsyn.parker@nzherald.co.nz|first=Tamsyn Parker Money Editor, NZ Herald|date=2017-05-16|work=NZ Herald|access-date=2018-10-06|language=en-NZ|issn=1170-0777}}</ref>\n\n===Savings & Investments===\nIn May 2018, Heartland's Direct Call Account received a 5-star rating from [[CANSTAR]] in its Flexible Saver and Regular Saver categories.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.canstar.co.nz/savings-accounts/make-savings-transaction-accounts-work/|title=Five-star savings and transaction accounts 2018 - Canstar|date=2018-05-29|work=Canstar|access-date=2018-10-06|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, Heartland launched a mobile app for its deposit customers to give them better control over their investments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/nz/app/heartland-mobile-app/id1401756383?mt=8|title=Heartland Mobile App|website=App\u00a0Store|language=en-AU|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/BU1809/S00225/heartland-releases-mobile-app-for-deposit-customers.htm|title=Heartland releases Mobile App for deposit customers  {{!}} Scoop News|website=www.scoop.co.nz|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, Heartland was named Canstar Bank of the Year \u2013 Savings.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.canstar.co.nz/savings-accounts/start-saving-honest-spending-heartland-advises/|title=Canstar Bank of the Year \u2013 Savings 2018: Heartland|date=2018-07-02|work=Canstar|access-date=2018-10-06|language=en-GB}}</ref> Canstar researched, analysed and compared 31 accounts from 11 providers for the annual ratings.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn April 2020, Heartland decided to not pass on interest rate reductions, after the Reserve bank dropped the OCR to a record low, as they looked to preserve their own profits, rather than looking after their customers.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.heartland.co.nz/}}\n\n{{New Zealand Building Societies}}\n{{NZ Banks |state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:Building societies of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Banks of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Ashburton, New Zealand]]\n", "name_user": "HeartlandBank", "label": "safe", "comment": "someone had written an awful comment.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heartland_Bank"}
